. Legal Advice in Crisis Training for Government Lawyers: Perspectives from the United States and Sweden -- tPart IV: Educating and Skill- Building -- t14. Call Air Traffic Control! Confronting Crisis as Lawyers and Teachers -- t15. Leveraging Lawyers’ Strengths and Training Them to Support Team Problem- Solving Under Crisis Conditions -- t16. Stay Calm and Carry On: How to Stay on Point When in a Crisis -- tConclusion -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbout the Editors -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aShines a light on the emerging field of law dedicated to responding to and resolving the crises of the twenty-first centuryIn an increasingly globalized world, a complex and interlocking web of nations, governments, non-state actors, laws, and rules affect human behavior. When crisis hits—whether that be extrajudicial detention, unprompted deportation, pandemics, or natural disasters—lawyers are increasingly among the first responders, equipped with the knowledge necessary to navigate the regulations of this ever more complex world.Crisis Lawyering explores this phenomenon and attempts to identify and define what it means to engage in the practice of law in crisis situations. In so doing, it hopes to sketch out the contours of the emerging field of crisis lawyering. Contributors to this volume explore cases surrounding domestic violence; dealing with immigrants in detention and banned from travel; policing in Ferguson, Missouri; the kidnapping of journalists; and climate change, among other crises. Their analysis not only serves as guidance to lawyers in such situations, but also helps others who deal with crises understand those crises—and the role of lawyers in them—better so that they may respond to them more effectively, efficiently, collaboratively and creatively. Crisis Lawyering shines a light on the emerging field of law dedicated to responding to and resolving the complex crises of the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEmergency managementxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aPractice of lawzUnited States. 7aLAW / Essays.2bisacsh  aCenter for Constitutional Rights.  aCivil Rights Division.  aCivil Rights.  aCoalition for the Homeless.  aConsolidated Edison.  aDOJ.  aFerguson.  aGuantánamo.  aICE.  aInter-American Commission on Human Rights (IACHR) police response.  aInternational human rights.  aJessica Lenahan.  aMeToo.  aMike Brown.  aMuslim Ban.  aNew York City.  aNew York State.  aRobert Hayes.  aSALT.  aUnited States Department of Justice.  aWar on Terror.  aauthoritarian legal structure.  aborder.  acivil rights.  aclients.  aclimate change.  aclinical legal education.  acollaboration.  acollaborative.  aconflicts-of-interest.  aconsent decree.  acooperative.  acreative coalition building.  acredible fear.  acriminal justice.  acrisis management.  adetention.  adisasters.  adomestic violence.  aeconomic democracy.  aelection protection.  aelections.  afamily separation.  afood insecurity.  afood-justice.  afood-sovereignty.  agender bias.  agood practice models.  agovernment institutions.  ahealth.  ahomelessness.  ahuman rights.  aimmigration.  aimpact litigation.  ainequality.  aintegrative lawyering.  ainteractive instructional design.  ainteragency advocacy.  ainteragency.  ajail.  ajournalists.  akidnapping.  alabor.  alaw clinic.  alawless space.  alegal education.  alegal ethics.  alessons.  alocal ordinances.  alocalization.  along term recovery.  amaritime law enforcement.  amaritime threat response.  amediation.  ameta-leadership.  amoral obligation.  amulti-agency colla